/* ============================================================================
   linux+ :: content/domain1.js
   Lazy-loaded textbook reading module for XK0-006 Domain 1 (System Management).
   Populates LINUXPLUS.reading[1]. Loaded on demand by app.js.
   ============================================================================ */
window.LINUXPLUS = window.LINUXPLUS || {}; LINUXPLUS.reading = LINUXPLUS.reading || {};
LINUXPLUS.reading[1] = [];
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"The Linux Boot Process: Firmware to Login", body:"<p>Understanding how a Linux machine transforms from powered-off silicon into a multi-user system is foundational to every troubleshooting task you will face. The boot process is a chain of hand-offs, and a failure at any link leaves the system stuck. The first link is <span class='keyterm'>firmware</span>, the low-level software baked into the motherboard that initializes hardware and locates a bootable device.</p><h3>BIOS versus UEFI</h3><p>Legacy <span class='keyterm'>BIOS</span> (Basic Input/Output System) is a 16-bit firmware that performs the POST (Power-On Self-Test), then reads the first 512 bytes of the boot disk, the <span class='keyterm'>MBR</span> (Master Boot Record), and executes the boot code stored there. BIOS is limited to disks of 2 TiB and a maximum of four primary partitions. Modern systems instead ship <span class='keyterm'>UEFI</span> (Unified Extensible Firmware Interface), a richer 32/64-bit environment that understands filesystems directly. UEFI reads bootloader files (<code>.efi</code> executables) from a dedicated FAT32 <span class='keyterm'>EFI System Partition (ESP)</span> mounted at <code>/boot/efi</code>, and it uses the GPT partition scheme, removing the old size and partition-count limits. The firmware keeps an ordered list of boot entries in NVRAM; on Linux you read and edit that list with <code>efibootmgr -v</code>, which shows each entry, its target <code>.efi</code> file, and the current <code>BootOrder</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Legacy BIOS</th><th>UEFI</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Boot data location</td><td>MBR (first 512 bytes)</td><td>.efi files on the ESP</td></tr><tr><td>Partition scheme</td><td>MBR</td><td>GPT</td></tr><tr><td>Max disk size</td><td>2 TiB</td><td>9.4 ZB (effectively unlimited)</td></tr><tr><td>Secure Boot</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Boot entry storage</td><td>None (code in MBR)</td><td>NVRAM variables</td></tr><tr><td>Pre-boot environment</td><td>16-bit, text</td><td>32/64-bit, GUI-capable</td></tr></tbody></table><p><span class='keyterm'>Secure Boot</span> is a UEFI feature that verifies the cryptographic signature of each bootloader and kernel before executing it, preventing unsigned or tampered code from loading. Distributions enroll a signed shim (<code>shim.efi</code>) signed by Microsoft's key so they boot on standard hardware. Check the current state with <code>mokutil --sb-state</code>; if a third-party (proprietary) driver fails to load on a Secure Boot machine, the driver is most likely unsigned.</p><h3>The Bootloader: GRUB2</h3><p>On most modern Linux systems the bootloader is <span class='keyterm'>GRUB2</span> (GRand Unified Bootloader version 2). GRUB2 presents the boot menu, lets you edit kernel command lines, and loads the selected kernel plus its initramfs into memory. Its runtime configuration lives in <code>/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</code> (Red Hat family) or <code>/boot/grub/grub.cfg</code> (Debian family). You never edit <code>grub.cfg</code> by hand; instead you edit <code>/etc/default/grub</code> and drop-in scripts under <code>/etc/grub.d/</code>, then regenerate the config with <code>grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg</code> (or <code>update-grub</code> on Debian). The <code>/boot</code> partition holds the kernel image (<code>vmlinuz</code>), the initramfs, and GRUB's modules.</p><table><thead><tr><th>File / command</th><th>Role</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>/etc/default/grub</code></td><td>Editable defaults: timeout, default entry, kernel args</td></tr><tr><td><code>/etc/grub.d/</code></td><td>Drop-in scripts that build menu entries</td></tr><tr><td><code>grub2-mkconfig -o ...</code></td><td>Regenerate grub.cfg (Red Hat)</td></tr><tr><td><code>update-grub</code></td><td>Regenerate grub.cfg (Debian wrapper)</td></tr><tr><td><code>grub2-install /dev/sda</code></td><td>Reinstall boot code to a disk</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Two GRUB defaults you will edit often are <code>GRUB_TIMEOUT</code> (how long the menu waits) and <code>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX</code> (parameters appended to every kernel line). To recover a forgotten root password you interrupt the menu, press <code>e</code> to edit the selected entry, append <code>rd.break</code> or <code>init=/bin/bash</code> to the kernel line, and press <code>Ctrl+x</code> to boot into a shell.</p><h3>PXE and the Boot Stages</h3><p>For diskless or mass-provisioned systems, <span class='keyterm'>PXE</span> (Preboot Execution Environment) lets the firmware request a boot image over the network using DHCP to find a server and TFTP to download the kernel and initramfs. PXE underpins automated installs (kickstart, preseed) and net-booted thin clients. The full boot order is: firmware (POST) to bootloader (GRUB2) to kernel to initramfs to <code>/sbin/init</code> (systemd as PID 1) to target units to login prompt.</p><h3>initrd and initramfs</h3><p>The <span class='keyterm'>initramfs</span> (initial RAM filesystem) is a compressed cpio archive containing a minimal root filesystem with the drivers and tools needed to mount the real root. The kernel cannot natively read an LVM volume, a RAID array, or an encrypted disk; the initramfs supplies those modules so the real root can be located, then it pivots to it. The older <code>initrd</code> was a block device image; <code>initramfs</code> superseded it. Rebuild it with <code>dracut --force</code> (Red Hat) or <code>update-initramfs -u</code> (Debian) after driver or storage changes, and inspect its contents with <code>lsinitrd</code> or <code>lsinitramfs</code> to confirm a needed module is actually inside. Forgetting this rebuild after changing the root storage stack is the classic cause of a system that drops to an emergency shell with <code>Cannot open root device</code>.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Memorize the boot order cold: firmware to bootloader to kernel to initramfs to init/systemd. If a system hangs in the initramfs emergency shell, suspect a missing storage driver or a bad UUID in <code>/etc/fstab</code> or the kernel command line. To edit the kernel line for one boot, press <code>e</code> in the GRUB menu; to make it permanent, edit <code>/etc/default/grub</code> and regenerate.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"The Linux Kernel and Kernel Space", body:"<p>The <span class='keyterm'>kernel</span> is the core program that sits between hardware and userspace applications. It owns the CPU scheduler, virtual memory, the filesystem layer, device drivers, and the network stack. Code running with full hardware privilege executes in <span class='keyterm'>kernel space</span>; ordinary applications run in <span class='keyterm'>user space</span> and request services through system calls. This separation is what stops a crashing application from taking down the whole machine.</p><h3>Monolithic with Loadable Modules</h3><p>Linux uses a <span class='keyterm'>monolithic kernel</span>: drivers and core subsystems share one address space for speed. To avoid a bloated, inflexible binary, Linux supports <span class='keyterm'>loadable kernel modules (LKMs)</span> with the <code>.ko</code> extension, which can be inserted and removed at runtime. This gives the performance of a monolithic design with the flexibility of a microkernel for hardware support. Modules live under <code>/lib/modules/$(uname -r)/</code>, and the running kernel image is in <code>/boot/vmlinuz-$(uname -r)</code>; multiple kernels can be installed side by side, which is why GRUB shows a list and lets you boot an older one when a new kernel misbehaves.</p><h3>The Kernel Ring Buffer and dmesg</h3><p>During boot and operation the kernel writes diagnostic messages to a fixed-size in-memory <span class='keyterm'>ring buffer</span>. The <code>dmesg</code> command prints it. Use <code>dmesg -T</code> for human-readable timestamps, <code>dmesg -l err,warn</code> to filter by priority, and <code>dmesg -w</code> to follow new messages live. This is the first place to look when a USB device, disk, or driver misbehaves. On systemd hosts the same kernel messages are also available through <code>journalctl -k</code>, with <code>journalctl -k -b -1</code> showing the kernel log from the previous boot -- essential when a crash prevents you from reading the current one.</p><h3>The /proc and /sys Pseudo-Filesystems</h3><p>The kernel exposes its state through two virtual filesystems that exist only in memory. <code>/proc</code> presents per-process directories (named by PID) plus system-wide files such as <code>/proc/cpuinfo</code>, <code>/proc/meminfo</code>, <code>/proc/cmdline</code> (the kernel boot line), and <code>/proc/mounts</code>. <code>/sys</code> (sysfs) presents a structured view of devices, drivers, and kernel objects, and is how <code>udev</code> learns about hardware. Neither consumes disk space; reading a file under them runs kernel code that returns live values.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Path / Command</th><th>What it reveals</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>uname -r</code></td><td>Running kernel release (e.g. 6.8.0-31-generic)</td></tr><tr><td><code>uname -a</code></td><td>Full kernel string: name, release, version, arch</td></tr><tr><td><code>uname -m</code></td><td>Machine hardware (x86_64, aarch64)</td></tr><tr><td><code>/proc/cmdline</code></td><td>Parameters passed to the kernel at boot</td></tr><tr><td><code>/proc/meminfo</code></td><td>Detailed memory usage and cache figures</td></tr><tr><td><code>/proc/version</code></td><td>Compiler and build details of the kernel</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Tuning Kernel Parameters with sysctl</h3><p>Many kernel behaviors are tunable at runtime through writable files under <code>/proc/sys/</code>. The <code>sysctl</code> command is the supported front end. <code>sysctl -a</code> lists every parameter, <code>sysctl net.ipv4.ip_forward</code> reads one, and <code>sysctl -w net.ipv4.ip_forward=1</code> sets it for the current session. Runtime changes are lost on reboot. To persist a setting, write it to <code>/etc/sysctl.conf</code> or, preferably, a drop-in file under <code>/etc/sysctl.d/</code>, then apply with <code>sysctl -p</code> or <code>sysctl --system</code>. Because parameter names map directly onto paths under <code>/proc/sys/</code> -- with dots becoming slashes -- the setting <code>net.ipv4.ip_forward</code> is simply the file <code>/proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward</code>, and reading or echoing into that file is equivalent to using <code>sysctl</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Controls</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>vm.swappiness</code></td><td>How aggressively the kernel swaps (0-100)</td></tr><tr><td><code>net.ipv4.ip_forward</code></td><td>Whether the host routes packets between interfaces</td></tr><tr><td><code>fs.file-max</code></td><td>System-wide cap on open file descriptors</td></tr><tr><td><code>kernel.hostname</code></td><td>The running hostname</td></tr><tr><td><code>net.ipv4.tcp_syncookies</code></td><td>SYN-flood protection toggle</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Loading the Kernel at Boot</h3><p>At boot the bootloader loads the compressed kernel image (<code>vmlinuz</code>) and the initramfs into memory and transfers control to the kernel, passing it the command-line parameters defined in the GRUB configuration. The kernel decompresses itself, initializes the CPU and memory management, mounts the initramfs as a temporary root, loads any drivers it needs to reach the real root device, then pivots to the real root filesystem and starts <code>/sbin/init</code> (systemd) as PID 1. You can view the exact line the running kernel was given in <code>/proc/cmdline</code>, and temporary changes to that line -- such as adding <code>single</code> for single-user mode or <code>nomodeset</code> to work around a graphics driver -- are made by editing the entry in the GRUB menu at boot, which is one of the most common recovery techniques.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Remember</div>Enabling IP forwarding turns a Linux box into a router. The runtime command <code>sysctl -w net.ipv4.ip_forward=1</code> takes effect immediately but does not survive a reboot unless the same line is added to a file under <code>/etc/sysctl.d/</code> and re-applied with <code>sysctl --system</code>.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"The Filesystem Hierarchy Standard (FHS)", body:"<p>Linux organizes everything into a single inverted tree that begins at the <span class='keyterm'>root directory</span>, written as <code>/</code>. There is no concept of drive letters; additional disks are grafted onto the tree at mount points. The <span class='keyterm'>Filesystem Hierarchy Standard (FHS)</span> defines what belongs where, so administrators and software can rely on a predictable layout across distributions.</p><h3>The Top-Level Directories</h3><p>Each top-level directory has a defined purpose. Knowing them lets you locate configuration, logs, and binaries on any system without guessing.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Directory</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>/boot</code></td><td>Kernel, initramfs, and GRUB files needed to boot</td></tr><tr><td><code>/etc</code></td><td>System-wide configuration files (all text, host-specific)</td></tr><tr><td><code>/home</code></td><td>Unprivileged users' personal directories</td></tr><tr><td><code>/root</code></td><td>The root user's home directory (not under /home)</td></tr><tr><td><code>/lib, /lib64</code></td><td>Essential shared libraries and kernel modules</td></tr><tr><td><code>/bin, /sbin</code></td><td>Essential user and system binaries (often symlinks into /usr)</td></tr><tr><td><code>/usr</code></td><td>Secondary hierarchy: most installed programs and libraries</td></tr><tr><td><code>/var</code></td><td>Variable data: logs, mail spools, caches, databases</td></tr><tr><td><code>/tmp</code></td><td>Temporary files, world-writable, often cleared on reboot</td></tr><tr><td><code>/opt</code></td><td>Self-contained add-on or third-party software packages</td></tr><tr><td><code>/dev</code></td><td>Device nodes for hardware and pseudo-devices</td></tr><tr><td><code>/proc, /sys</code></td><td>Virtual kernel filesystems (process and device state)</td></tr><tr><td><code>/run</code></td><td>Volatile runtime data (PIDs, sockets) since last boot</td></tr><tr><td><code>/mnt, /media</code></td><td>Temporary and removable-media mount points</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Logs, Configuration, and Binaries</h3><p>Three locations matter most day to day. <code>/etc</code> holds plain-text <span class='keyterm'>configuration files</span> such as <code>/etc/fstab</code>, <code>/etc/passwd</code>, and <code>/etc/ssh/sshd_config</code>; because they are text, they are easy to version, diff, and back up. <code>/var/log</code> holds logs, where you read <code>/var/log/syslog</code>, <code>/var/log/messages</code>, and the systemd journal. <code>/usr</code> holds the bulk of programs in <code>/usr/bin</code> and <code>/usr/sbin</code>. On modern distributions the legacy <code>/bin</code>, <code>/sbin</code>, and <code>/lib</code> are symbolic links into <code>/usr</code>, a change known as the <span class='keyterm'>usr-merge</span>.</p><h3>Finding Files and the System Binaries Split</h3><p>Several commands locate files by FHS convention. <code>which sshd</code> reports the first matching executable in your <code>PATH</code>; <code>type cd</code> distinguishes builtins from external commands; <code>whereis</code> finds the binary, source, and man page; and <code>locate</code> searches a pre-built database (refresh it with <code>updatedb</code>) for instant filename matches anywhere on disk.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Path pair</th><th>Distinction</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>/bin</code> vs <code>/usr/bin</code></td><td>Essential-at-boot vs general user programs</td></tr><tr><td><code>/sbin</code> vs <code>/usr/sbin</code></td><td>System/admin binaries, boot-critical vs not</td></tr><tr><td><code>/etc</code> vs <code>/usr/share</code></td><td>Host-specific config vs read-only shared data</td></tr><tr><td><code>/tmp</code> vs <code>/var/tmp</code></td><td>Cleared on reboot vs preserved across reboots</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Absolute versus Relative Paths</h3><p>An <span class='keyterm'>absolute path</span> starts at the root and is unambiguous from anywhere, for example <code>/var/log/syslog</code>. A <span class='keyterm'>relative path</span> is interpreted from your current working directory, so <code>../config/app.conf</code> means go up one level then into <code>config</code>. The shortcuts <code>.</code> (current directory), <code>..</code> (parent), and <code>~</code> (your home) are essential. Scripts should generally use absolute paths to avoid surprises when run from a different directory. A related concept is the <span class='keyterm'>symbolic link</span>, a pointer file created with <code>ln -s /real/target linkname</code> that the FHS relies on heavily -- the usr-merge itself is implemented as symlinks, and <code>/etc/localtime</code> is typically a symlink into <code>/usr/share/zoneinfo</code>. A <span class='keyterm'>hard link</span>, made with <code>ln</code> without <code>-s</code>, is a second name for the same inode and cannot cross filesystems or point at directories.</p><h3>Why the Split Between /usr and the Root</h3><p>The FHS draws a deliberate line between what must be available very early in boot and what can wait. Files needed to mount <code>/usr</code> and bring the system to a usable state -- the essential binaries, the kernel modules in <code>/lib/modules</code>, and the configuration in <code>/etc</code> -- traditionally lived on the root filesystem so the machine could reach single-user mode even if <code>/usr</code> was on a separate, not-yet-mounted volume. Everything non-essential -- the bulk of applications, documentation, and shared libraries -- lives under <code>/usr</code>, which can be large and even shared read-only across many hosts. A second important split is data that varies. Anything that grows or changes during normal operation belongs under <code>/var</code> (logs, mail, print queues, package caches, databases) so that the rest of the system can in principle be mounted read-only. This separation is why a well-designed server often puts <code>/var</code> and <code>/home</code> on their own partitions: a runaway log or a user filling their home directory then cannot exhaust the root filesystem and crash the whole machine.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A disk fills and the system slows. You run <code>df -h</code> and see <code>/var</code> at 100 percent. The culprit is almost always runaway logs in <code>/var/log</code> or an oversized package cache in <code>/var/cache</code> -- both are exactly where the FHS says variable, growing data lives. Use <code>du -sh /var/* | sort -h</code> to find the offending subtree.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"Server Architectures and Linux Distributions", body:"<p>Linux runs on a wider range of processors than any other operating system, and the Linux+ exam expects you to recognize the major architectures and the two great families of distributions. The architecture determines which package binaries will run; the distribution family determines which tools you use to manage them.</p><h3>CPU Architectures</h3><p>The dominant server and desktop architecture is <span class='keyterm'>x86_64</span>, also called <span class='keyterm'>AMD64</span>, the 64-bit extension of Intel's x86 instruction set. <span class='keyterm'>AArch64</span> (64-bit ARM) now powers cloud instances, Raspberry Pi, and Apple silicon, prized for performance per watt. <span class='keyterm'>RISC-V</span> is an open, royalty-free instruction set gaining traction in embedded and research systems. You can check a running system's architecture with <code>uname -m</code> or <code>lscpu</code>. The architecture matters because a binary built for one instruction set will not run on another: an <code>.rpm</code> or <code>.deb</code> tagged <code>aarch64</code>/<code>arm64</code> cannot be installed on an <code>x86_64</code> host, which is why repositories publish a separate package set per architecture and why container images are often multi-arch.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Architecture</th><th>Also called</th><th>Typical use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>x86_64</td><td>AMD64, x64</td><td>Mainstream servers, desktops, laptops</td></tr><tr><td>AArch64</td><td>ARM64</td><td>Cloud, mobile, SBCs, Apple silicon</td></tr><tr><td>RISC-V</td><td>riscv64</td><td>Embedded, academic, emerging hardware</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The Two Distribution Families</h3><p>Nearly every distribution descends from one of two packaging lineages, and they differ in package format and management tools. The <span class='keyterm'>RPM family</span> (Red Hat Enterprise Linux, Fedora, Rocky, AlmaLinux, CentOS Stream, SUSE) uses <code>.rpm</code> packages managed by <code>dnf</code> (the modern replacement for <code>yum</code>) and the low-level <code>rpm</code> tool. The <span class='keyterm'>Debian family</span> (Debian, Ubuntu, Linux Mint) uses <code>.deb</code> packages managed by <code>apt</code> and the low-level <code>dpkg</code> tool.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>RPM family</th><th>Debian family</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Package format</td><td>.rpm</td><td>.deb</td></tr><tr><td>High-level tool</td><td>dnf / yum</td><td>apt</td></tr><tr><td>Low-level tool</td><td>rpm</td><td>dpkg</td></tr><tr><td>Examples</td><td>RHEL, Fedora, Rocky, SUSE</td><td>Debian, Ubuntu, Mint</td></tr></tbody></table><p>The split matters in practice because the same software is packaged differently and the commands diverge. On a Red Hat host you run <code>dnf install httpd</code> and the service is named <code>httpd</code>; on Debian you run <code>apt install apache2</code> and the service is <code>apache2</code>. Repository definitions live in <code>/etc/yum.repos.d/</code> for the RPM family and in <code>/etc/apt/sources.list</code> plus <code>/etc/apt/sources.list.d/</code> for the Debian family. Querying which package owns a file uses <code>rpm -qf /path</code> versus <code>dpkg -S /path</code>. Recognizing these conventions lets you orient instantly on an unfamiliar host.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Operation</th><th>RPM family (dnf)</th><th>Debian family (apt)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Install</td><td><code>dnf install pkg</code></td><td><code>apt install pkg</code></td></tr><tr><td>Remove</td><td><code>dnf remove pkg</code></td><td><code>apt remove pkg</code></td></tr><tr><td>Update index / upgrade</td><td><code>dnf upgrade</code></td><td><code>apt update &amp;&amp; apt upgrade</code></td></tr><tr><td>Search</td><td><code>dnf search term</code></td><td><code>apt search term</code></td></tr><tr><td>List installed</td><td><code>rpm -qa</code></td><td><code>dpkg -l</code></td></tr><tr><td>Which package owns file</td><td><code>rpm -qf /path</code></td><td><code>dpkg -S /path</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Rolling versus Point Releases</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>point release</span> distribution (RHEL, Debian stable, Ubuntu LTS) freezes a tested set of package versions and ships periodic numbered releases, prioritizing stability and a long support window -- ideal for production servers. A <span class='keyterm'>rolling release</span> (Arch, openSUSE Tumbleweed, Fedora Rawhide) continuously updates packages to the newest upstream versions with no fixed milestones, giving the latest software at the cost of more frequent change. Enterprise environments overwhelmingly choose point releases for predictability, pairing them with long-term support windows -- Ubuntu LTS releases get five years of standard support, and RHEL major versions get roughly a decade -- so that a server can be deployed once and patched without disruptive version jumps. Rolling releases shine on developer workstations where having the newest toolchains outweighs the cost of frequent updates.</p><h3>Identifying a Host and Its Release</h3><p>On an unfamiliar machine, the fastest neutral way to learn the distribution and version is <code>cat /etc/os-release</code>, a standardized file present on every modern distro that reports the <code>NAME</code>, <code>VERSION_ID</code>, and <code>ID_LIKE</code> (the family it derives from). Older RPM systems also keep <code>/etc/redhat-release</code>, and <code>lsb_release -a</code> prints a summary when the LSB tools are installed. Combined with the package-tool tell, these let you classify any host in seconds: read <code>/etc/os-release</code>, note whether <code>dnf</code> or <code>apt</code> exists, and you know both the exact release and which management commands apply. This habit matters because nearly every later task -- installing software, finding service names, locating config -- branches on that single fact.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>If a question shows <code>dnf install</code> or <code>rpm -qa</code>, the host is in the Red Hat family. If it shows <code>apt install</code> or <code>dpkg -l</code>, it is Debian/Ubuntu. The package tool is the fastest tell for which family you are working with.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"The Graphical Stack: Display Managers, X11, and Wayland", body:"<p>Although servers frequently run without a screen, the Linux+ exam covers the graphical stack because administrators manage workstations and must understand the difference between text and graphical operation. The graphical stack is a layered system: a display server draws pixels, a display manager handles login, and a desktop environment provides the user interface.</p><h3>X11 versus Wayland</h3><p>The traditional display server is the <span class='keyterm'>X Window System</span>, commonly the <code>Xorg</code> implementation of <span class='keyterm'>X11</span>. It uses a network-transparent client-server model in which applications (clients) talk to the X server, even across a network. Its age shows in complexity and security weaknesses. <span class='keyterm'>Wayland</span> is the modern replacement: a leaner protocol in which the <span class='keyterm'>compositor</span> combines the roles of display server and window manager, offering better security and smoother graphics. Most current distributions default to Wayland but keep an Xorg session available for compatibility.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>X11 (Xorg)</th><th>Wayland</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Age / model</td><td>1980s client-server</td><td>Modern compositor-based</td></tr><tr><td>Network transparency</td><td>Built in (X forwarding)</td><td>Not native (needs extras)</td></tr><tr><td>Security isolation</td><td>Weak (clients can snoop)</td><td>Strong per-client isolation</td></tr><tr><td>Status</td><td>Legacy, still supported</td><td>Default on most distros</td></tr></tbody></table><p>You can tell which server a session is running under at runtime by checking the <code>XDG_SESSION_TYPE</code> environment variable, which reads <code>wayland</code> or <code>x11</code>; <code>loginctl show-session $XDG_SESSION_ID -p Type</code> confirms it from the session manager's view. A practical reason the distinction still matters is remote graphics: X11's built-in network transparency means <code>ssh -X host</code> can display a remote application's window on your local screen, whereas Wayland requires a separate mechanism such as RDP, VNC, or pipewire-based screen sharing.</p><h3>Display Managers</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>display manager</span> presents the graphical login screen and starts a session after authentication. Common ones are <span class='keyterm'>GDM</span> (GNOME Display Manager), <span class='keyterm'>LightDM</span>, and <span class='keyterm'>SDDM</span> (used with KDE Plasma). The display manager runs as a systemd service; you can identify the active one by checking which service the <code>display-manager.service</code> symlink points to.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Display manager</th><th>Paired desktop</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>GDM</td><td>GNOME (Fedora, RHEL, Ubuntu)</td></tr><tr><td>SDDM</td><td>KDE Plasma</td></tr><tr><td>LightDM</td><td>XFCE, MATE, lightweight desktops</td></tr><tr><td>LXDM</td><td>LXDE / LXQt</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Desktop Environments</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>desktop environment (DE)</span> is the complete user interface -- panels, file manager, window controls, and applications. GNOME and KDE Plasma are the heavyweights; XFCE, MATE, and Cinnamon are lighter alternatives popular on older hardware. It helps to keep the layers distinct: the display server (Xorg or Wayland) draws pixels and handles input, the display manager handles login and session selection, and the desktop environment is what the user actually interacts with after logging in. A single machine can have several desktop environments installed, and the display manager's session menu lets the user pick which one to start, and on X11 systems whether to run it under Xorg or Wayland.</p><h3>Remote Desktops and Troubleshooting</h3><p>Administrators often need a graphical session on a machine across the network. <span class='keyterm'>VNC</span> shares an entire desktop frame-buffer and is platform-neutral but unencrypted by default, so it is tunneled through SSH. <span class='keyterm'>RDP</span>, served on Linux by <code>xrdp</code>, is the Windows remote-desktop protocol and integrates cleanly with Windows clients. <span class='keyterm'>X11 forwarding</span> (<code>ssh -X</code>) is lighter still, painting a single remote application's window on your local display rather than a whole desktop. When a graphical session fails to start, the first checks are which <code>display-manager.service</code> is active, whether the system reached <code>graphical.target</code>, and the Xorg log at <code>/var/log/Xorg.0.log</code> or the journal for the compositor, where a missing or mismatched GPU driver is the usual culprit. Booting with the kernel argument <code>nomodeset</code> is a common workaround that forces a generic display mode so you can at least reach a usable screen and fix the real driver.</p><h3>Headless Servers and systemd Targets</h3><p>Servers usually run <span class='keyterm'>headless</span>, with no monitor and no graphical stack, to save resources. Systemd represents the overall system state with <span class='keyterm'>targets</span>. <code>graphical.target</code> boots the system with the display manager and a GUI, while <code>multi-user.target</code> provides full networking and services but only text consoles -- the standard choice for servers. Switch at runtime with <code>systemctl isolate multi-user.target</code> and set the default with <code>systemctl set-default multi-user.target</code>. These targets replace the older SysV runlevels (runlevel 5 maps to graphical, runlevel 3 to multi-user). Check the current default with <code>systemctl get-default</code>. A headless server that has no graphics stack installed at all cannot reach <code>graphical.target</code> even if asked, so installing a package group like the GNOME desktop is a prerequisite to switching a server into GUI mode.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Remember</div>To permanently boot a server to text mode and free its graphics resources, run <code>systemctl set-default multi-user.target</code>. To return to a desktop, set the default back to <code>graphical.target</code> and reboot or isolate it.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"Kernel Module Management", body:"<p>Kernel modules are pieces of driver and feature code that the kernel loads and unloads on demand. Managing them correctly is essential when a piece of hardware is not recognized, when you must disable a buggy driver, or when you need to pass options to a driver at load time.</p><h3>Inspecting Modules</h3><p>List the modules currently loaded with <code>lsmod</code>, which reads <code>/proc/modules</code> and shows each module's size and what depends on it. To learn about a specific module -- its description, parameters, file path, and dependencies -- use <code>modinfo e1000e</code>. These two commands answer most starting questions about what is loaded and what a module does.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>lsmod</code></td><td>List currently loaded modules</td></tr><tr><td><code>modinfo &lt;mod&gt;</code></td><td>Show details and parameters of a module</td></tr><tr><td><code>modprobe &lt;mod&gt;</code></td><td>Load a module and its dependencies</td></tr><tr><td><code>modprobe -r &lt;mod&gt;</code></td><td>Unload a module (and unused deps)</td></tr><tr><td><code>insmod &lt;file.ko&gt;</code></td><td>Insert one module file, no dependency handling</td></tr><tr><td><code>rmmod &lt;mod&gt;</code></td><td>Remove one module, no dependency handling</td></tr><tr><td><code>depmod</code></td><td>Rebuild the module dependency database</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>modprobe versus insmod and rmmod</h3><p>The high-level tool is <span class='keyterm'>modprobe</span>. It consults the dependency map built by <code>depmod</code> (stored in <code>modules.dep</code>) and loads any prerequisite modules automatically. To unload, use <code>modprobe -r</code>, which also removes now-unused dependencies. By contrast <span class='keyterm'>insmod</span> and <span class='keyterm'>rmmod</span> operate on a single module file with no dependency resolution; they are lower-level and rarely the right choice. Always prefer <code>modprobe</code> in practice.</p><h3>Persistent Configuration</h3><p>Two configuration directories control modules across reboots. Files in <code>/etc/modules-load.d/*.conf</code> list modules to load automatically at boot. Files in <code>/etc/modprobe.d/*.conf</code> set options and aliases, for example <code>options snd_hda_intel power_save=1</code>, and are also where you perform <span class='keyterm'>blacklisting</span>. To stop a driver from ever loading, add a line like <code>blacklist nouveau</code> in a file under <code>/etc/modprobe.d/</code>; this is the standard way to disable an open-source GPU driver before installing a proprietary one.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Location / directive</th><th>Effect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>/etc/modules-load.d/*.conf</code></td><td>Load the listed modules at every boot</td></tr><tr><td><code>/etc/modprobe.d/*.conf</code></td><td>Options, aliases, blacklists</td></tr><tr><td><code>options &lt;mod&gt; key=val</code></td><td>Pass a parameter to a module at load</td></tr><tr><td><code>blacklist &lt;mod&gt;</code></td><td>Prevent loading by name</td></tr><tr><td><code>install &lt;mod&gt; /bin/true</code></td><td>Stronger block; defeats dependency loads</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Rebuilding the initramfs</h3><p>Because some modules must be present before the root filesystem mounts, they are baked into the <span class='keyterm'>initramfs</span>. After blacklisting a driver or adding a storage module, rebuild the initramfs with <code>dracut --force</code> on Red Hat systems or <code>update-initramfs -u</code> on Debian systems. The older <code>mkinitrd</code> command has been superseded by <code>dracut</code>. Forgetting this step is a classic reason a blacklist appears to have no effect. A quick way to confirm whether a module is currently loaded is <code>lsmod | grep nouveau</code>; if it still appears after a reboot, the blacklist did not take, and the initramfs is the usual reason.</p><h3>Passing Parameters and Reading the Map</h3><p>Many drivers accept options that change their behavior. You can supply them at load time on the command line, as in <code>modprobe usbcore autosuspend=-1</code>, or persist them in an <code>options</code> line under <code>/etc/modprobe.d/</code>. To discover what a given module accepts, <code>modinfo -p &lt;module&gt;</code> lists each parameter with a short description. The dependency map that <code>modprobe</code> relies on is generated by <code>depmod</code> and stored as <code>/lib/modules/$(uname -r)/modules.dep</code>; after manually installing a new module file you run <code>depmod -a</code> so <code>modprobe</code> can resolve it. Two other forms of blacklisting exist beyond the <code>blacklist</code> keyword: an <code>install &lt;module&gt; /bin/true</code> line makes any attempt to load the module run a no-op instead, which is a stronger block because it defeats loading by dependency, not just by name. Modern kernels can also enforce module signing: when Secure Boot is active, the kernel refuses to load an unsigned third-party module and logs <code>module verification failed</code>, which is why proprietary drivers must be signed and their key enrolled with <code>mokutil</code> before they will load. You can audit how a module was tainted or blocked through <code>dmesg</code>, and confirm a module's signing status in the tail of <code>modinfo</code> output, where a <code>sig_id</code> and signer appear for signed modules.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Blacklisting alone may not be enough if the module is already in the initramfs. After adding <code>blacklist nouveau</code> to <code>/etc/modprobe.d/</code>, regenerate the initramfs with <code>dracut --force</code> (or <code>update-initramfs -u</code>) and reboot for the change to take full effect.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"Hardware Discovery and Device Tools", body:"<p>Before you can configure or troubleshoot hardware you must be able to enumerate it. Linux ships a family of inventory commands, each focused on a class of devices, plus the <code>/dev</code> tree and the <code>udev</code> subsystem that create and name device nodes dynamically.</p><h3>The ls-family Inventory Tools</h3><p>A cluster of commands beginning with <code>ls</code> reports on connected hardware. <code>lspci</code> lists devices on the PCI bus -- network cards, GPUs, storage controllers; add <code>-v</code> or <code>-k</code> to see the kernel driver in use. <code>lsusb</code> lists USB devices. <code>lscpu</code> summarizes the CPU: architecture, cores, threads, cache, and virtualization flags. <code>lsmem</code> and <code>lsblk</code> report memory ranges and block devices respectively.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Reports on</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>lspci</code></td><td>PCI devices (NICs, GPUs, controllers)</td></tr><tr><td><code>lsusb</code></td><td>USB devices and hubs</td></tr><tr><td><code>lscpu</code></td><td>CPU model, cores, threads, flags</td></tr><tr><td><code>lsmem</code></td><td>Online memory blocks and ranges</td></tr><tr><td><code>lshw</code></td><td>Full hardware tree (run as root)</td></tr><tr><td><code>dmidecode</code></td><td>SMBIOS/DMI data from firmware tables</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Deeper Inventory: lshw and dmidecode</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>lshw</span> walks the entire hardware tree and prints a detailed report; <code>lshw -short</code> gives a readable summary and <code>lshw -class memory</code> narrows the focus. <span class='keyterm'>dmidecode</span> reads the SMBIOS/DMI tables the firmware exposes, revealing details that are not visible at runtime such as the exact RAM module part numbers, maximum supported memory, and BIOS version. Use <code>dmidecode -t memory</code> or <code>dmidecode -t bios</code> to target a record type.</p><h3>Sensors and Server Management</h3><p>On physical servers, <span class='keyterm'>lm_sensors</span> exposes temperature, fan, and voltage readings; run <code>sensors-detect</code> once to configure it, then <code>sensors</code> to read values. <span class='keyterm'>ipmitool</span> talks to the server's out-of-band BMC (Baseboard Management Controller) to read sensor data, query the hardware event log, and power-cycle the machine remotely, even when the OS is down. Disk health is read separately with <code>smartctl -a /dev/sda</code>, which queries the drive's SMART attributes for reallocated sectors and predicted failures.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Need</th><th>Command</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Driver bound to a PCI device</td><td><code>lspci -k</code></td></tr><tr><td>USB device tree</td><td><code>lsusb -t</code></td></tr><tr><td>Temperatures and fans</td><td><code>sensors</code></td></tr><tr><td>Out-of-band power/sensors</td><td><code>ipmitool</code></td></tr><tr><td>Disk SMART health</td><td><code>smartctl -a /dev/sda</code></td></tr><tr><td>Live device hot-plug events</td><td><code>udevadm monitor</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The /dev Directory and udev</h3><p>The <code>/dev</code> directory contains <span class='keyterm'>device nodes</span>, special files that represent hardware and pseudo-devices such as <code>/dev/sda</code> (a disk), <code>/dev/null</code>, and <code>/dev/random</code>. These nodes are created dynamically at runtime by <span class='keyterm'>udev</span>, the device manager, which watches kernel events and applies rules from <code>/etc/udev/rules.d/</code>. Udev rules let you give a device a persistent, predictable name regardless of plug order -- for example forcing a specific USB-serial adapter to always appear as <code>/dev/ttyUSB-modem</code>. Device nodes carry a major and minor number that the kernel uses to route I/O to the right driver; you can see them in the output of <code>ls -l /dev</code>, where the file type character is <code>b</code> for block devices like disks and <code>c</code> for character devices like terminals and serial ports. When a device is hot-plugged, the kernel emits a uevent, udev matches it against the rules, creates the node under <code>/dev</code>, and can run helper programs -- this is how a freshly inserted USB drive appears as <code>/dev/sdb</code> and gets auto-mounted on a desktop. Monitor these events live with <code>udevadm monitor</code>, and dump everything the system knows about a device with <code>udevadm info /dev/sda</code>, which is invaluable when writing a matching rule. After editing a rule file, reload and re-apply without rebooting using <code>udevadm control --reload</code> followed by <code>udevadm trigger</code>.</p><h3>Pseudo-Devices and Block versus Character</h3><p>Not every node in <code>/dev</code> maps to physical hardware. The kernel exposes several <span class='keyterm'>pseudo-devices</span> that are pure software: <code>/dev/null</code> discards anything written to it and returns end-of-file when read, <code>/dev/zero</code> produces an endless stream of zero bytes (handy for wiping or pre-filling a file with <code>dd</code>), and <code>/dev/random</code> and <code>/dev/urandom</code> supply cryptographic randomness. These appear constantly in scripts -- redirecting unwanted output to <code>/dev/null</code> is the canonical way to silence a command. The block-versus-character distinction is fundamental: <span class='keyterm'>block devices</span> (disks, marked <code>b</code>) are addressed in fixed-size blocks and buffered, while <span class='keyterm'>character devices</span> (terminals, serial ports, marked <code>c</code>) stream data byte by byte. The major number selects the driver and the minor number the specific device, which is why two partitions on one disk share a major but differ in minor.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Remember</div>When runtime tools cannot tell you the maximum RAM a board supports or the exact DIMM part number, <code>dmidecode -t memory</code> reads it straight from the firmware's SMBIOS tables -- information the kernel does not surface through <code>lsmem</code>.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"Storage Foundations: Disks, Partitions, and Partition Tables", body:"<p>Storage management starts with understanding how Linux sees disks and how those disks are divided. A physical disk is a <span class='keyterm'>block device</span>, meaning the kernel reads and writes it in fixed-size blocks. Before a disk can hold filesystems it is usually divided into <span class='keyterm'>partitions</span>, and the map of those partitions is the partition table.</p><h3>MBR versus GPT</h3><p>There are two partition table schemes. The legacy <span class='keyterm'>MBR</span> (Master Boot Record) stores the table in the first 512 bytes, supports disks up to 2 TiB, and allows only four primary partitions (worked around with one extended partition holding logical partitions). The modern <span class='keyterm'>GPT</span> (GUID Partition Table) supports disks far larger than 2 TiB, allows up to 128 partitions by default, and stores a backup copy of the table at the end of the disk for resilience. UEFI systems require GPT. GPT also embeds a <span class='keyterm'>protective MBR</span> in the first sector so legacy tools that do not understand GPT see one large partition rather than empty space and refuse to overwrite it, guarding against accidental destruction.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>MBR</th><th>GPT</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Max disk size</td><td>2 TiB</td><td>~9.4 ZB</td></tr><tr><td>Primary partitions</td><td>4 (or 3 + extended)</td><td>128 (default)</td></tr><tr><td>Backup table</td><td>No</td><td>Yes (end of disk)</td></tr><tr><td>Firmware</td><td>BIOS</td><td>UEFI (and BIOS)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Device Naming</h3><p>SATA and SAS disks appear as <code>/dev/sda</code>, <code>/dev/sdb</code>, and so on, with partitions numbered <code>/dev/sda1</code>, <code>/dev/sda2</code>. NVMe SSDs use a different scheme: <code>/dev/nvme0n1</code> is the first namespace of the first NVMe controller, and its first partition is <code>/dev/nvme0n1p1</code> -- note the <code>p</code> before the partition number. Virtual disks under KVM often appear as <code>/dev/vda</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Device pattern</th><th>Bus / type</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>/dev/sda</code>, <code>/dev/sdb1</code></td><td>SATA / SAS / USB disks</td></tr><tr><td><code>/dev/nvme0n1</code>, <code>/dev/nvme0n1p1</code></td><td>NVMe SSD (controller, namespace, partition)</td></tr><tr><td><code>/dev/vda</code>, <code>/dev/vda1</code></td><td>VirtIO virtual disk (KVM guest)</td></tr><tr><td><code>/dev/mapper/vg-lv</code></td><td>LVM logical volume or device-mapper target</td></tr><tr><td><code>/dev/sr0</code></td><td>Optical drive</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Partitioning Tools</h3><p>Several tools edit partition tables. <span class='keyterm'>fdisk</span> traditionally handled MBR but modern versions also handle GPT. <span class='keyterm'>gdisk</span> is the GPT-focused equivalent. <span class='keyterm'>parted</span> is a scriptable tool that handles both schemes and can resize partitions. To inspect rather than edit, <code>lsblk</code> shows the tree of disks, partitions, and mountpoints, and <code>blkid</code> prints each partition's UUID and filesystem type -- the UUID is what you reference in <code>/etc/fstab</code> for stable mounting. After any change made outside the kernel's view, run <code>partprobe</code> so the kernel re-reads the partition table without a reboot; otherwise the new partition may not appear under <code>/dev</code> until you reboot.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>lsblk</code></td><td>Tree of block devices and mountpoints</td></tr><tr><td><code>blkid</code></td><td>UUIDs and filesystem types</td></tr><tr><td><code>fdisk -l</code></td><td>List partitions on all disks</td></tr><tr><td><code>parted</code></td><td>Create/resize MBR or GPT partitions</td></tr><tr><td><code>growpart /dev/sda 1</code></td><td>Grow a partition to fill free space</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Growing Partitions in the Cloud</h3><p>When a cloud provider enlarges a virtual disk, the partition does not grow automatically. The <span class='keyterm'>growpart</span> tool expands a partition to consume newly available space, for example <code>growpart /dev/sda 1</code> grows the first partition. You then grow the filesystem on top of it separately. Note the space between the disk and the partition number, which differs from the usual concatenated device name. If the kernel has not noticed the disk's new size, run <code>partprobe</code> or <code>echo 1 &gt; /sys/block/sda/device/rescan</code> so it re-reads the geometry before you attempt to grow anything.</p><h3>Partition Types and Alignment</h3><p>Each partition carries a <span class='keyterm'>partition type</span> code that hints at its intended use -- Linux filesystem, Linux swap, EFI System Partition, or Linux LVM, among others. On GPT these are GUIDs; on MBR they are one-byte hex codes (for example <code>83</code> for Linux, <code>8e</code> for LVM, <code>82</code> for swap). The type does not enforce content but helps tools and firmware locate the right partition, which is why the ESP must be flagged correctly for UEFI to find the bootloader. Modern partitioning tools automatically align partitions to one-megabyte boundaries so that filesystem blocks line up with the underlying flash erase blocks and RAID stripes; misalignment silently degrades SSD and array performance. When in doubt, let <code>parted</code> or <code>fdisk</code> choose default start sectors rather than entering them by hand. Always confirm you are operating on the intended disk with <code>lsblk</code> before writing a new table, because committing a partition table to the wrong device destroys whatever was there.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>NVMe naming trips people up: the first partition of <code>/dev/nvme0n1</code> is <code>/dev/nvme0n1p1</code>, not <code>/dev/nvme0n11</code>. The <code>p</code> separator avoids ambiguity between the namespace number and the partition number.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"Logical Volume Manager (LVM)", body:"<p>Fixed partitions are inflexible: resizing them is risky and they cannot easily span multiple disks. The <span class='keyterm'>Logical Volume Manager (LVM)</span> adds an abstraction layer that lets you pool storage from several disks and carve out resizable volumes on demand. It is the standard way to manage storage on enterprise Linux servers.</p><h3>The Three Layers</h3><p>LVM stacks three concepts. A <span class='keyterm'>Physical Volume (PV)</span> is a whole disk or partition initialized for LVM use. One or more PVs are grouped into a <span class='keyterm'>Volume Group (VG)</span>, a single pool of storage. From that pool you carve out <span class='keyterm'>Logical Volumes (LVs)</span>, which behave like partitions and receive filesystems. The key advantage is that an LV can be grown or shrunk, and a VG can be enlarged by adding more PVs, all while the system runs. Under the hood, the VG's space is divided into fixed-size <span class='keyterm'>physical extents</span> (4 MiB by default), and an LV is simply a set of those extents stitched together; this is what lets a single logical volume span several disks transparently and lets you migrate its extents with <code>pvmove</code>. The resulting device appears under two equivalent paths, <code>/dev/vg_data/lv_web</code> and <code>/dev/mapper/vg_data-lv_web</code>, because LVM is built on the kernel's device-mapper subsystem.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Layer</th><th>Create</th><th>Inspect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Physical Volume</td><td><code>pvcreate /dev/sdb</code></td><td><code>pvs</code> / <code>pvdisplay</code></td></tr><tr><td>Volume Group</td><td><code>vgcreate data /dev/sdb</code></td><td><code>vgs</code> / <code>vgdisplay</code></td></tr><tr><td>Logical Volume</td><td><code>lvcreate -L 20G -n web data</code></td><td><code>lvs</code> / <code>lvdisplay</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>A Step-by-Step Provisioning Narrative</h3><p>Suppose a new 500 GB disk arrives as <code>/dev/sdb</code> and you must give the web server a 20 GB volume. First, initialize the disk as a PV: <code>pvcreate /dev/sdb</code>. Next, create a volume group from it: <code>vgcreate vg_data /dev/sdb</code>. Now carve a logical volume: <code>lvcreate -L 20G -n lv_web vg_data</code>, which creates the device <code>/dev/vg_data/lv_web</code>. Put a filesystem on it with <code>mkfs.xfs /dev/vg_data/lv_web</code>, then mount it and add it to <code>/etc/fstab</code>. Months later the web data outgrows 20 GB. You extend the LV with <code>lvextend -L +10G /dev/vg_data/lv_web</code>, then grow the filesystem to match: <code>xfs_growfs /mount/point</code> for XFS or <code>resize2fs /dev/vg_data/lv_web</code> for ext4. The convenient <code>lvextend -r</code> flag does both the extend and the filesystem grow in one step. If the whole VG is full, add another disk with <code>vgextend vg_data /dev/sdc</code> first. This pattern -- extend the PV pool, extend the LV, grow the filesystem -- is the single most tested LVM workflow, so commit its order to memory.</p><h3>Resizing, Snapshots, and Thin Provisioning</h3><p>The whole point of LVM is online flexibility, so the resize commands are worth memorizing. Growing is always safe; shrinking an ext4 volume requires shrinking the filesystem first, and XFS cannot shrink at all.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Goal</th><th>Command</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Grow LV + filesystem together</td><td><code>lvextend -r -L +10G /dev/vg/lv</code></td></tr><tr><td>Grow to use all free VG space</td><td><code>lvextend -r -l +100%FREE /dev/vg/lv</code></td></tr><tr><td>Add a disk to the pool</td><td><code>vgextend vg /dev/sdc</code></td></tr><tr><td>Shrink ext4 LV (offline-ish)</td><td><code>lvreduce -r -L 10G /dev/vg/lv</code></td></tr><tr><td>Create a snapshot</td><td><code>lvcreate -s -L 5G -n snap /dev/vg/lv</code></td></tr><tr><td>Move data off a failing PV</td><td><code>pvmove /dev/sdb</code></td></tr></tbody></table><p>An LVM <span class='keyterm'>snapshot</span> captures a point-in-time view of a volume using copy-on-write, ideal for taking a consistent backup of a busy database without downtime: <code>lvcreate -s -L 5G -n snap_web /dev/vg_data/lv_web</code>. The snapshot only stores blocks that change after it was taken, so size it for the expected write volume during the backup window -- if it fills, the snapshot becomes invalid. <span class='keyterm'>Thin provisioning</span> lets you create logical volumes whose advertised size exceeds the physically allocated space, drawing real blocks from a shared thin pool only as data is written -- efficient, but you must monitor the pool with <code>lvs -a</code> so it does not run out, because an exhausted thin pool can take every volume on it offline. The <code>pvmove</code> command relocates the extents of a logical volume off one physical volume onto another while the system runs, which is how you retire a failing disk without downtime: move the data, then <code>vgreduce</code> the old PV out of the group.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A database volume is at 95 percent and a SAN-provided disk has just been attached as <code>/dev/sdc</code>. The fix without downtime: <code>pvcreate /dev/sdc</code>, then <code>vgextend vg_db /dev/sdc</code>, then <code>lvextend -r -L +50G /dev/vg_db/lv_db</code>. The <code>-r</code> flag grows the XFS or ext4 filesystem in the same operation.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"Linux Filesystems and Filesystem Utilities", body:"<p>A partition or logical volume is just raw space until you write a <span class='keyterm'>filesystem</span> onto it -- the structure that organizes files, directories, and metadata. Linux supports many filesystems, and choosing the right one and maintaining it are core administrative skills.</p><h3>The Major Filesystems</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>ext4</span> is the long-standing default on Debian and Ubuntu: stable, well understood, and a safe general choice. <span class='keyterm'>XFS</span> is the default on RHEL and excels with large files and high parallelism. <span class='keyterm'>Btrfs</span> is a modern copy-on-write filesystem with built-in snapshots, checksums, and pooling. <span class='keyterm'>tmpfs</span> lives entirely in RAM and is used for <code>/tmp</code> and <code>/run</code>, vanishing on reboot. <span class='keyterm'>vfat/FAT</span> provides cross-platform compatibility and is required on the UEFI ESP.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Filesystem</th><th>Strengths</th><th>Typical use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>ext4</td><td>Mature, reliable, can shrink</td><td>General-purpose default (Debian/Ubuntu)</td></tr><tr><td>XFS</td><td>Scales to huge files, fast parallel I/O</td><td>RHEL default, databases, big data</td></tr><tr><td>Btrfs</td><td>Snapshots, checksums, subvolumes</td><td>Advanced setups, openSUSE</td></tr><tr><td>tmpfs</td><td>RAM-backed, very fast, volatile</td><td>/tmp, /run, caches</td></tr><tr><td>vfat / FAT32</td><td>Universal compatibility</td><td>EFI System Partition, USB sticks</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Journaling and Inodes</h3><p>ext4, XFS, and Btrfs are <span class='keyterm'>journaling</span> filesystems: before committing changes they record the intended operation in a journal, so an unexpected power loss leaves the filesystem recoverable in seconds rather than requiring a full scan. This is why journaling filesystems dominate on servers. Every file is tracked by an <span class='keyterm'>inode</span>, a metadata record holding ownership, permissions, timestamps, and block pointers but not the filename. A filesystem can exhaust its inodes while disk space remains -- common when an application creates millions of tiny files -- producing a confusing <code>No space left on device</code> error even though <code>df -h</code> shows free space. The tell-tale is <code>df -i</code>, which reports inode usage separately; ext4 fixes the inode count at creation time, while XFS allocates inodes dynamically and rarely hits this wall.</p><h3>Creating, Checking, and Tuning</h3><p>Create a filesystem with the <code>mkfs</code> family: <code>mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdb1</code> or <code>mkfs.xfs /dev/sdb1</code>. Check and repair an unmounted ext filesystem with <code>fsck</code> (which dispatches to <code>e2fsck</code>); XFS uses its own repair tool, <code>xfs_repair</code>, because <code>fsck.xfs</code> does nothing by design. Grow filesystems with <code>resize2fs</code> for ext4 and <code>xfs_growfs</code> for XFS. Note an important asymmetry: ext4 can be shrunk while XFS cannot be shrunk at all. Tune ext filesystems with <code>tune2fs</code> -- for example <code>tune2fs -L data /dev/sdb1</code> sets a label, <code>tune2fs -l</code> dumps superblock details, and <code>tune2fs -m 1</code> lowers the percentage of blocks reserved for root. The <span class='keyterm'>superblock</span> is the metadata structure describing the filesystem's size, block layout, and state; ext4 keeps backup copies so a damaged primary superblock can be recovered with <code>e2fsck -b 32768 /dev/sdb1</code>, pointing at a known backup location. Two more everyday tools round out maintenance: <code>df -h</code> reports free space per mounted filesystem, while <code>du -sh /path</code> sums the actual usage of a directory tree -- the pair you reach for when a disk fills. When a filesystem is mounted, the kernel will refuse a <code>fsck</code> and you should never force one, because checking a live filesystem races against the kernel's own writes and can corrupt it; instead unmount it, or for the root filesystem schedule a check at the next boot or run it from a rescue environment.</p><h3>Choosing a Filesystem</h3><p>Match the filesystem to the workload. For a general-purpose Debian or Ubuntu server, ext4 is the dependable default and the only mainstream choice that can be shrunk. For a Red Hat host, large-file workloads, or databases with heavy parallel I/O, XFS is the standard and scales better under load. Choose Btrfs when you specifically want its snapshots, checksumming, and subvolume features and are comfortable with its added complexity. Use tmpfs wherever you want fast scratch space that need not survive a reboot, and reserve vfat/FAT for interoperability and the mandatory EFI System Partition. A useful rule of thumb: if the question stresses shrinking a volume, the answer is ext4; if it stresses huge files or RHEL defaults, the answer is XFS.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Task</th><th>ext4</th><th>XFS</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Create</td><td><code>mkfs.ext4</code></td><td><code>mkfs.xfs</code></td></tr><tr><td>Check/repair</td><td><code>fsck</code> / <code>e2fsck</code></td><td><code>xfs_repair</code></td></tr><tr><td>Grow</td><td><code>resize2fs</code></td><td><code>xfs_growfs</code></td></tr><tr><td>Shrink</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Never run <code>fsck</code> on a mounted filesystem -- it can corrupt data. Unmount first, or fix the root filesystem from a rescue boot. And remember XFS cannot shrink: if a question asks you to reduce a volume, only ext4 supports it.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"Software RAID with mdadm", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>RAID</span> (Redundant Array of Independent Disks) combines multiple disks to gain performance, fault tolerance, or both. Linux can build RAID in software using the kernel's <span class='keyterm'>md</span> (multiple device) driver, managed by the <code>mdadm</code> utility -- no special controller required.</p><h3>RAID Levels</h3><p>The level determines the trade-off between speed, capacity, and redundancy. RAID 0 stripes data for speed but offers no redundancy -- one failed disk loses everything. RAID 1 mirrors data across disks for redundancy at the cost of half your capacity. RAID 5 stripes with one distributed parity block, surviving one disk failure. RAID 6 uses two parity blocks and survives two failures. RAID 10 combines mirroring and striping for both speed and redundancy. The key intuition is that parity levels (5 and 6) trade write performance and rebuild risk for capacity efficiency, while mirroring levels (1 and 10) trade capacity for fast, low-risk recovery -- which is why databases with heavy random writes often favor RAID 10 despite its 50 percent overhead.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Min disks</th><th>Fault tolerance</th><th>Capacity</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>RAID 0</td><td>2</td><td>None</td><td>100% (striped)</td></tr><tr><td>RAID 1</td><td>2</td><td>1 disk</td><td>50% (mirror)</td></tr><tr><td>RAID 5</td><td>3</td><td>1 disk</td><td>N-1 disks</td></tr><tr><td>RAID 6</td><td>4</td><td>2 disks</td><td>N-2 disks</td></tr><tr><td>RAID 10</td><td>4</td><td>1 per mirror</td><td>50%</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Building and Managing an Array</h3><p>Create an array with <code>mdadm --create /dev/md0 --level=5 --raid-devices=3 /dev/sdb /dev/sdc /dev/sdd</code>. Watch the rebuild and check status with <code>cat /proc/mdstat</code>, which shows progress bars and which disks are active. Inspect a specific array in detail with <code>mdadm --detail /dev/md0</code>. After creation, save the configuration to <code>/etc/mdadm/mdadm.conf</code> so the array reassembles on boot; <code>mdadm --assemble</code> brings an existing array back online. A <span class='keyterm'>hot spare</span> added with <code>--spare-devices</code> sits idle until a member fails, then the array automatically rebuilds onto it.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>mdadm --create</code></td><td>Build a new array</td></tr><tr><td><code>mdadm --assemble</code></td><td>Activate an existing array</td></tr><tr><td><code>mdadm --detail /dev/md0</code></td><td>Show array status and members</td></tr><tr><td><code>cat /proc/mdstat</code></td><td>Live array state and rebuild progress</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>RAID versus LVM, Hardware versus Software</h3><p>RAID provides redundancy; <span class='keyterm'>LVM</span> provides flexible volume management. They are complementary -- a common design layers LVM on top of an md RAID array to get both. <span class='keyterm'>Hardware RAID</span> uses a dedicated controller card with its own processor and battery-backed cache, offloading parity work from the CPU and presenting the array as a single disk to the OS. <span class='keyterm'>Software RAID</span> with mdadm uses the host CPU and is portable across controllers, cheaper, and fully visible to the OS, but consumes some CPU for parity calculations.</p><h3>Failures, Rebuilds, and Monitoring</h3><p>When a member disk fails, a redundant array (RAID 1, 5, 6, or 10) keeps serving data in a degraded state. You mark a disk as failed with <code>mdadm /dev/md0 --fail /dev/sdc</code>, remove it with <code>--remove</code>, then add the replacement with <code>--add</code>, and the array automatically rebuilds onto the new disk while <code>/proc/mdstat</code> shows progress. Rebuilds are I/O-intensive and, on large RAID 5 arrays, lengthy -- a window during which a second failure would be fatal, which is the main argument for RAID 6 on big arrays. For unattended operation, run <code>mdadm --monitor</code> as a service so that a failed disk triggers an email alert rather than going unnoticed until a second drive dies. Understanding the parity math helps on the exam: RAID 5 usable capacity is the size of one disk times the count minus one, and RAID 6 is the count minus two, because that space is consumed by parity rather than data. A worked example: six 4 TB disks in RAID 6 yield (6 minus 2) times 4 TB, or 16 TB usable, while the same six disks in RAID 10 yield only 12 TB because half the raw capacity goes to mirrors. After replacing a disk, you must also tell the firmware or initramfs about the new layout if the array is your boot device, and you re-add the rescued configuration with <code>mdadm --assemble --scan</code> reading <code>/etc/mdadm/mdadm.conf</code>. Growing an existing array onto an added disk is possible with <code>mdadm --grow</code>, but it is a slow reshape operation that should be run with a backup in hand.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Remember</div>RAID is not a backup. It protects against drive failure, not against deletion, ransomware, or corruption, all of which propagate instantly across mirrors and stripes. Always maintain independent backups in addition to RAID.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"Mounting Storage: /etc/fstab, mount, and Network Shares", body:"<p>A filesystem is useless until it is <span class='keyterm'>mounted</span>, attached to a directory in the tree called a <span class='keyterm'>mount point</span>. You mount manually for one-off needs and declare permanent mounts in a configuration file so they survive reboots.</p><h3>The mount and umount Commands</h3><p>Mount a device with <code>mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt/data</code>; the kernel often auto-detects the filesystem type, or you specify it with <code>-t xfs</code>. Pass options with <code>-o</code>, for example <code>mount -o ro,noexec /dev/sdb1 /mnt/data</code>. Detach with <code>umount /mnt/data</code> (or <code>umount /dev/sdb1</code>); if it reports the target is busy, find the offending process with <code>lsof</code> or <code>fuser -m</code>. Run <code>mount</code> with no arguments, or read <code>/etc/mtab</code> or <code>/proc/mounts</code>, to see what is currently mounted. The <code>findmnt</code> command presents the same information as a readable tree and accepts a path or device to query a single mount.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Mount option</th><th>Effect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>ro</code> / <code>rw</code></td><td>Read-only / read-write</td></tr><tr><td><code>noexec</code></td><td>Forbid executing binaries from the mount</td></tr><tr><td><code>nosuid</code></td><td>Ignore setuid/setgid bits</td></tr><tr><td><code>nodev</code></td><td>Ignore device nodes on the mount</td></tr><tr><td><code>noatime</code></td><td>Skip access-time updates (faster)</td></tr><tr><td><code>_netdev</code></td><td>Wait for the network before mounting</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The /etc/fstab File</h3><p>The <span class='keyterm'>/etc/fstab</span> file lists filesystems to mount automatically at boot. Each line has six whitespace-separated fields.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1. Device</td><td>UUID, label, or path like /dev/sdb1</td></tr><tr><td>2. Mount point</td><td>Directory to attach it to</td></tr><tr><td>3. Type</td><td>Filesystem: ext4, xfs, nfs, cifs</td></tr><tr><td>4. Options</td><td>defaults, ro, noexec, _netdev, etc.</td></tr><tr><td>5. Dump</td><td>0 (off) for the legacy dump tool</td></tr><tr><td>6. Pass</td><td>fsck order: 1 root, 2 others, 0 skip</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Referencing a partition by <span class='keyterm'>UUID</span> (from <code>blkid</code>) rather than <code>/dev/sdb1</code> is best practice, because device names can change between boots while UUIDs are stable. After editing fstab, validate with <code>mount -a</code>, which mounts everything listed; an error here, rather than a failed boot, is the safe way to catch a typo.</p><h3>Identifiers and Bind Mounts</h3><p>You can reference a device three ways in field one, and the choice affects reliability. A raw kernel name like <code>/dev/sdb1</code> is fragile because enumeration order can change when disks are added. A <code>UUID=</code> reference is the recommended default: it is unique and travels with the filesystem. A <code>LABEL=</code> reference is human-friendly but you must keep labels unique yourself. A <span class='keyterm'>bind mount</span> makes an existing directory appear at a second location with <code>mount --bind /data /var/www/data</code> (or <code>none /var/www/data none bind 0 0</code> in fstab), which is how you expose one tree inside a chroot or container without copying it.</p><table><thead><tr><th>fstab device form</th><th>When to use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>/dev/sdb1</code></td><td>Quick tests only; fragile across reboots</td></tr><tr><td><code>UUID=...</code></td><td>Recommended default; stable and unique</td></tr><tr><td><code>LABEL=...</code></td><td>Readable, if you keep labels unique</td></tr><tr><td><code>/dev/vg/lv</code></td><td>LVM volumes; names are already stable</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Network Shares: NFS and SMB/CIFS</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>NFS</span> (Network File System) is the native Unix file-sharing protocol; mount a share with <code>mount -t nfs server:/export /mnt/nfs</code>. <span class='keyterm'>SMB/CIFS</span> is the Windows file-sharing protocol; mount it with <code>mount -t cifs //server/share /mnt/smb -o username=user</code>, usually with a credentials file for the password. In fstab, network mounts need the <code>_netdev</code> option so the system waits for networking before attempting them. The <span class='keyterm'>autofs</span> service mounts network shares on demand when a path is accessed and unmounts them when idle, saving resources and avoiding boot delays from unreachable servers; its maps live in <code>/etc/auto.master</code> and the map files it references. This on-demand approach is far more robust than a static fstab entry for an unreliable server, because an fstab network mount with the wrong options can stall the entire boot waiting for a host that may be down. Common mount options shape behavior and security: <code>ro</code> mounts read-only, <code>rw</code> read-write, <code>noexec</code> forbids running binaries from the mount, <code>nosuid</code> ignores setuid bits, <code>nodev</code> ignores device nodes, and <code>noatime</code> skips updating access times for a performance gain. These hardening options are routinely applied to <code>/tmp</code> and to removable or network media to limit what an attacker can do with a mounted volume. Mounting <code>/tmp</code> with <code>noexec,nosuid,nodev</code> is a classic baseline hardening step, since a world-writable directory is a favorite staging ground for dropped malware.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Always run <code>mount -a</code> after editing <code>/etc/fstab</code>. A bad entry can stop the system from booting into multi-user mode and drop it into an emergency shell. Testing with <code>mount -a</code> surfaces the mistake while you still have a working shell, and adding the <code>nofail</code> option to non-critical entries lets the boot continue even if that device is absent.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"Network Interface Configuration: NetworkManager, nmcli, and Netplan", body:"<p>Configuring network interfaces is a daily task. Modern Linux has largely standardized on two management layers: <span class='keyterm'>NetworkManager</span> on Red Hat and Fedora systems, and <span class='keyterm'>Netplan</span> on Ubuntu. Both replace the old practice of hand-editing per-interface scripts.</p><h3>Interfaces and Predictable Naming</h3><p>A network <span class='keyterm'>interface</span> is the OS representation of a NIC. Modern distributions use <span class='keyterm'>predictable network interface names</span> derived from hardware location, such as <code>enp0s3</code> or <code>eno1</code>, instead of the old <code>eth0</code>, so names stay consistent across reboots and hardware changes. List interfaces with <code>ip link</code>.</p><h3>NetworkManager and nmcli</h3><p>NetworkManager stores configuration as <span class='keyterm'>connection profiles</span> and is driven from the command line by <code>nmcli</code>. A profile decouples the configuration from the device: you can define several profiles for one interface (home, office, static) and activate whichever you need, and a profile survives even when the cable is unplugged. You add a static profile, modify it, and bring it up:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Task</th><th>Command</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>List devices</td><td><code>nmcli device status</code></td></tr><tr><td>List connections</td><td><code>nmcli connection show</code></td></tr><tr><td>Add static IP</td><td><code>nmcli con add type ethernet ifname enp0s3 ipv4.method manual ipv4.addresses 192.168.1.10/24 ipv4.gateway 192.168.1.1</code></td></tr><tr><td>Modify a profile</td><td><code>nmcli con mod &lt;name&gt; ipv4.dns 8.8.8.8</code></td></tr><tr><td>Activate</td><td><code>nmcli con up &lt;name&gt;</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Netplan on Ubuntu</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Netplan</span> reads YAML files in <code>/etc/netplan/*.yaml</code> and renders them to a backend (NetworkManager on desktops, systemd-networkd on servers). A static configuration sets <code>dhcp4: no</code>, an <code>addresses</code> list, a <code>routes</code> default gateway, and <code>nameservers</code>. Apply changes with <code>netplan apply</code>, or test risky changes safely with <code>netplan try</code>, which automatically rolls back after a timeout if you do not confirm -- invaluable when configuring a remote machine you could otherwise lock yourself out of. YAML is whitespace-sensitive, so indentation errors are a common failure; validate with <code>netplan generate</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>NetworkManager (nmcli)</th><th>Netplan</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Config style</td><td>Keyfiles / live commands</td><td>Declarative YAML</td></tr><tr><td>Stored in</td><td><code>/etc/NetworkManager/system-connections/</code></td><td><code>/etc/netplan/*.yaml</code></td></tr><tr><td>Apply changes</td><td><code>nmcli con up</code></td><td><code>netplan apply</code> / <code>try</code></td></tr><tr><td>Typical distro</td><td>RHEL, Fedora</td><td>Ubuntu</td></tr><tr><td>Safe remote test</td><td>--</td><td><code>netplan try</code> (auto-revert)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Static versus DHCP, Hosts, and Hostname</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>static</span> address is fixed in configuration and suits servers; <span class='keyterm'>DHCP</span> leases an address automatically and suits clients. The <code>/etc/hosts</code> file provides local name-to-IP mappings that are consulted before DNS, useful for small fixed mappings. Set the system hostname with <code>hostnamectl set-hostname web01.example.com</code>, which updates <code>/etc/hostname</code> and takes effect immediately; <code>hostnamectl</code> alone shows the current hostname and related metadata such as the machine ID, operating system, kernel, and architecture. One more layer worth knowing is the backend renderer: on Ubuntu servers Netplan typically targets <span class='keyterm'>systemd-networkd</span>, the lightweight systemd network manager, while on desktops it targets NetworkManager; on Red Hat systems NetworkManager is used directly and its profiles are stored as keyfiles under <code>/etc/NetworkManager/system-connections/</code>. Whichever backend is in play, the principle is the same -- you describe the desired state declaratively and let the manager apply it -- which is why hand-editing the old per-interface scripts is now discouraged and, on many distributions, no longer even consulted.</p><h3>Bonds, Bridges, and VLANs</h3><p>Beyond simple interfaces, NetworkManager and Netplan both express aggregate constructs that the exam touches on. A <span class='keyterm'>bond</span> (or team) joins two NICs into one logical link for redundancy or higher throughput, with modes such as active-backup for failover and 802.3ad for switch-negotiated aggregation. A <span class='keyterm'>bridge</span> behaves like a virtual switch and is what connects virtual machines or containers to the physical LAN. A <span class='keyterm'>VLAN</span> interface tags traffic with an 802.1Q ID so one physical port carries several isolated networks. In <code>nmcli</code> you create these with connection types <code>bond</code>, <code>bridge</code>, and <code>vlan</code>; in Netplan they appear as top-level <code>bonds:</code>, <code>bridges:</code>, and <code>vlans:</code> blocks. Verify the result with <code>ip -d link show</code>, whose <code>-d</code> flag prints the bond mode, bridge membership, or VLAN ID that a plain <code>ip link</code> hides. Bonding state is also visible under <code>/proc/net/bonding/bond0</code>, which names the active slave and reports each member's link status -- the first place to look when a bonded server loses redundancy.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>You must change the IP of a server you can only reach over SSH. On Ubuntu, edit the Netplan YAML and run <code>netplan try</code> rather than <code>netplan apply</code>. If the new settings break your connection, Netplan auto-reverts after the timeout and your SSH session survives, sparing you a trip to the console.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"Name Resolution and Network Diagnostic Tools", body:"<p>When networking misbehaves, a systematic toolkit lets you isolate whether the problem is the link, the route, name resolution, or the remote service. The Linux+ exam expects fluency with both name resolution configuration and the diagnostic commands.</p><h3>How Names Become Addresses</h3><p>Name resolution is governed by two files. <span class='keyterm'>/etc/nsswitch.conf</span> defines the order of sources for the <code>hosts</code> database, typically <code>files dns</code>, meaning check <code>/etc/hosts</code> first then DNS. <span class='keyterm'>/etc/resolv.conf</span> lists the DNS <code>nameserver</code> entries and the default <code>search</code> domain. On systemd-resolved systems this file is often a symlink to <code>/run/systemd/resolve/stub-resolv.conf</code> managed automatically, so you configure DNS through NetworkManager or Netplan rather than editing it directly; on those hosts <code>resolvectl status</code> shows the real per-link DNS servers that a glance at <code>resolv.conf</code> would miss. A third file, <code>/etc/hosts</code>, holds static name-to-IP mappings that <code>nsswitch.conf</code> consults before DNS, which is the fastest way to override resolution for a single host or to break a chicken-and-egg dependency during setup.</p><h3>DNS Lookup Tools</h3><p>Three tools query DNS. <code>dig example.com</code> is the detailed, scriptable choice and shows the full answer, authority, and timing; <code>dig +short</code> trims it to the answer. You can query a specific record type with <code>dig MX example.com</code> or aim a query at a particular resolver with <code>dig @8.8.8.8 example.com</code>, which is how you prove whether your local DNS or an upstream one is at fault. <code>host example.com</code> gives a concise summary, and <code>nslookup</code> offers an interactive mode, though <code>dig</code> is generally preferred for troubleshooting because its output exposes the TTL, the responding server, and whether the answer was authoritative.</p><h3>The ip Suite and Connection Tools</h3><p>The modern <code>ip</code> command replaces the deprecated <code>ifconfig</code>, <code>route</code>, and <code>arp</code>. Use <code>ip address</code> (or <code>ip a</code>) to view addresses, <code>ip link</code> for interface state, and <code>ip route</code> for the routing table. <code>ss</code> replaces the old <code>netstat</code> and lists sockets; <code>ss -tulpn</code> shows listening TCP/UDP ports and the owning processes.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Legacy command</th><th>Modern replacement</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>ifconfig</code></td><td><code>ip address</code> / <code>ip link</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>route -n</code></td><td><code>ip route</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>arp -n</code></td><td><code>ip neigh</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>netstat -tulpn</code></td><td><code>ss -tulpn</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>netstat -r</code></td><td><code>ip route</code></td></tr></tbody></table><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>ip a / ip link / ip route</code></td><td>Addresses, interfaces, routing table</td></tr><tr><td><code>ss -tulpn</code></td><td>Listening sockets and their processes</td></tr><tr><td><code>ping</code></td><td>Basic ICMP reachability and latency</td></tr><tr><td><code>traceroute / mtr</code></td><td>Hop-by-hop path; mtr is continuous</td></tr><tr><td><code>dig / host / nslookup</code></td><td>DNS resolution queries</td></tr><tr><td><code>ethtool</code></td><td>NIC link speed, duplex, and driver</td></tr><tr><td><code>tcpdump</code></td><td>Capture and inspect packets</td></tr><tr><td><code>nmap</code></td><td>Scan hosts and open ports</td></tr><tr><td><code>nc (netcat)</code></td><td>Test a port, transfer data raw</td></tr><tr><td><code>curl</code></td><td>Test HTTP/HTTPS endpoints</td></tr><tr><td><code>iperf3</code></td><td>Measure throughput between hosts</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>A Troubleshooting Workflow</h3><p>Work up the stack. Confirm the interface has an address with <code>ip a</code>. Test the gateway with <code>ping</code>, then a public IP like <code>ping 8.8.8.8</code> to prove routing. If the IP pings but names fail, the problem is DNS -- verify with <code>dig example.com</code> and check <code>/etc/resolv.conf</code>. To prove a remote service is listening, use <code>nc -vz host 443</code> or <code>curl -I https://host</code>. For path problems, <code>mtr host</code> shows where packets are lost, and <code>ethtool eth0</code> confirms the link negotiated the expected speed and duplex. A duplex mismatch -- one side at full duplex, the other at half -- produces the classic symptom of a link that works but is mysteriously slow and lossy under load, which <code>ethtool</code> exposes immediately. For deeper inspection, <code>tcpdump -i eth0 port 443</code> captures live packets so you can confirm whether traffic is even reaching the host and what the remote end is replying, while <code>arp -n</code> or <code>ip neigh</code> reveals whether the host has resolved the MAC address of its gateway -- an empty or incomplete neighbor entry points to a layer-2 problem on the local segment. Throughput complaints are settled objectively with <code>iperf3</code>: run <code>iperf3 -s</code> on one host and <code>iperf3 -c &lt;server&gt;</code> on the other to measure the actual bandwidth between them, distinguishing a genuine network bottleneck from an application that is simply slow.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>The classic distinguishing test: if <code>ping 8.8.8.8</code> succeeds but <code>ping google.com</code> fails, networking and routing are fine and the fault is DNS. Check <code>/etc/resolv.conf</code> and <code>/etc/nsswitch.conf</code> next, and on systemd hosts confirm the real resolver with <code>resolvectl status</code> rather than trusting the symlinked <code>resolv.conf</code>.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"The Shell Environment: Variables and Startup Files", body:"<p>The <span class='keyterm'>shell</span> is the command interpreter you type into, most commonly <code>bash</code>. Its behavior is shaped by variables and a set of startup files that run when a session begins. Understanding these is essential for setting up environments, paths, and reproducible behavior.</p><h3>Shell versus Environment Variables</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>shell variable</span> exists only in the current shell: <code>name=value</code> (no spaces around the equals). An <span class='keyterm'>environment variable</span> is exported so that child processes inherit it: <code>export name=value</code>. Reference a variable with <code>$name</code> and view all environment variables with <code>env</code> or <code>printenv</code>. Key environment variables include <code>PATH</code> (the colon-separated list of directories searched for commands), <code>HOME</code> (your home directory), <code>SHELL</code> (your login shell), <code>USER</code>, and <code>PS1</code> (the prompt format). The distinction is enforced by the shell: a plain assignment lives only in the current process, so a script you launch will not see it, whereas <code>export</code> marks the variable for inheritance by every child. You can run a command with a one-off variable by prefixing it, as in <code>LANG=C sort file</code>, which sets <code>LANG</code> for that single invocation without touching your environment, and you can remove a variable entirely with <code>unset name</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Variable</th><th>Holds</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>PATH</code></td><td>Directories searched for executables</td></tr><tr><td><code>HOME</code></td><td>The current user's home directory</td></tr><tr><td><code>SHELL</code></td><td>Path to the user's login shell</td></tr><tr><td><code>PWD</code></td><td>Current working directory</td></tr><tr><td><code>PS1</code></td><td>Primary prompt string</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Login versus Non-Login Shells</h3><p>The startup files that run depend on the session type. A <span class='keyterm'>login shell</span> (you log in at a console or over SSH) reads <code>/etc/profile</code> and then the first it finds of <code>~/.bash_profile</code>, <code>~/.bash_login</code>, or <code>~/.profile</code>. A <span class='keyterm'>non-login interactive shell</span> (you open a new terminal in an existing session) reads <code>~/.bashrc</code> and the system-wide <code>/etc/bash.bashrc</code>. This distinction explains a classic confusion: settings placed only in <code>.bash_profile</code> do not appear in new terminal tabs, while settings only in <code>.bashrc</code> are missing from a fresh SSH login. A third category, the <span class='keyterm'>non-interactive shell</span> that runs a script, reads neither file by default; instead it consults whatever file the <code>BASH_ENV</code> variable names, if any. There is also a logout hook: <code>~/.bash_logout</code> runs when a login shell exits, commonly used to clear the screen or wipe a temporary directory. Knowing exactly which files fire for which session type is the difference between a configuration that works everywhere and one that mysteriously applies in some terminals but not others.</p><table><thead><tr><th>File</th><th>When it runs</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>/etc/profile</code></td><td>System-wide, login shells</td></tr><tr><td><code>~/.bash_profile</code></td><td>Per-user, login shells</td></tr><tr><td><code>~/.bashrc</code></td><td>Per-user, non-login interactive shells</td></tr><tr><td><code>/etc/bash.bashrc</code></td><td>System-wide interactive shells</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Aliases, History, and Best Practice</h3><p>An <span class='keyterm'>alias</span> is a shorthand for a command, defined with <code>alias ll='ls -lh'</code> and conventionally placed in <code>~/.bashrc</code>. <span class='keyterm'>Command history</span> is saved to <code>~/.bash_history</code>; recall commands with the up arrow, search with <code>Ctrl+R</code>, list with <code>history</code>, rerun by number with <code>!42</code>, and repeat the previous command with <code>!!</code> (often <code>sudo !!</code> after a permission denial). A related construct is the shell <span class='keyterm'>function</span>, which unlike an alias accepts arguments and can hold several commands, making it the right tool when an alias is too limited. The common convention is to put interactive customizations (aliases, prompt, functions) in <code>~/.bashrc</code> and have <code>~/.bash_profile</code> source <code>~/.bashrc</code> so both session types get the same setup. After editing a startup file you can apply it to the current shell without logging out by sourcing it: <code>source ~/.bashrc</code> (or the equivalent shorthand <code>. ~/.bashrc</code>) re-reads the file in place. For system-wide settings that should apply to every user, the modern approach is to drop a small script into <code>/etc/profile.d/</code> rather than editing <code>/etc/profile</code> directly, because the drop-in directory survives package updates and keeps changes modular. Several environment variables tune history behavior: <code>HISTSIZE</code> sets how many commands are kept in memory, <code>HISTFILESIZE</code> how many are saved to disk, and <code>HISTCONTROL=ignoredups</code> suppresses consecutive duplicate entries. The shell also offers brace and tilde expansion that scripts lean on: <code>~user</code> expands to that user's home, and <code>{a,b,c}</code> generates a list, so <code>mkdir /srv/{web,db,cache}</code> creates three directories at once. Understanding when the shell performs each expansion -- and that single quotes suppress all of it while double quotes still allow variable expansion -- prevents a whole class of quoting bugs in everyday commands and scripts.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Remember</div>To add a directory to your <code>PATH</code> permanently, append <code>export PATH=\"$PATH:/opt/app/bin\"</code> to <code>~/.bashrc</code> (or <code>/etc/profile.d/</code> for all users). Putting it only in <code>.bash_profile</code> means new terminal tabs will not see it.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"Redirection, Pipes, and Core Text-Processing Utilities", body:"<p>The power of the Linux command line comes from connecting small tools together. Every process has three standard streams, and the shell lets you redirect them to files or pipe them between commands to build sophisticated one-liners.</p><h3>The Three Standard Streams</h3><p>Each process opens three <span class='keyterm'>file descriptors</span>: <span class='keyterm'>stdin</span> (0) for input, <span class='keyterm'>stdout</span> (1) for normal output, and <span class='keyterm'>stderr</span> (2) for error messages. Keeping stdout and stderr separate lets you save results while still seeing or logging errors independently.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Operator</th><th>Effect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>&gt;</code></td><td>Redirect stdout to a file (overwrite)</td></tr><tr><td><code>&gt;&gt;</code></td><td>Redirect stdout to a file (append)</td></tr><tr><td><code>&lt;</code></td><td>Read stdin from a file</td></tr><tr><td><code>&lt;&lt;</code></td><td>Here-document (inline input)</td></tr><tr><td><code>2&gt;</code></td><td>Redirect stderr</td></tr><tr><td><code>2&gt;&amp;1</code></td><td>Send stderr to wherever stdout goes</td></tr><tr><td><code>&amp;&gt;</code></td><td>Redirect both stdout and stderr</td></tr><tr><td><code>|</code></td><td>Pipe stdout of one command into another</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Pipes and tee</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>pipe</span> (<code>|</code>) connects one command's stdout to the next command's stdin, as in <code>ps aux | grep nginx</code>. The <code>tee</code> command splits a stream, writing it to a file and passing it onward, so <code>command | tee out.log</code> saves output while still displaying it; add <code>tee -a</code> to append rather than overwrite. Discard unwanted output by redirecting to <code>/dev/null</code>, the bit bucket -- <code>command 2&gt;/dev/null</code> silences only errors while still showing results. A pipe only forwards stdout, not stderr, which is why you sometimes add <code>2&gt;&amp;1</code> before a pipe to send both streams into the next command. The <code>xargs</code> tool bridges the gap when a command takes arguments rather than stdin, as in <code>find . -name '*.log' | xargs rm</code>, building command lines from piped input.</p><h3>The Text-Processing Toolkit</h3><p>A handful of filters cover most text work. <span class='keyterm'>grep</span> searches for patterns (<code>grep -i error log</code>, <code>grep -r</code> to recurse). <span class='keyterm'>sed</span> is a stream editor for substitutions, as in <code>sed 's/old/new/g'</code>. <span class='keyterm'>awk</span> is a field-aware processor: <code>awk '{print $1}'</code> prints the first column. <code>cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd</code> extracts a delimited field, <code>sort</code> and <code>uniq -c</code> order and count lines, and <code>wc -l</code> counts them. <code>head</code> and <code>tail</code> show the start or end of a file, and <code>tail -f</code> follows a growing log live. <code>tr</code> translates or deletes characters, and <code>find</code> locates files by name, size, time, or type, optionally running an action with <code>-exec</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Job</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>grep</code></td><td>Find lines matching a pattern</td></tr><tr><td><code>sed</code></td><td>Stream-edit / substitute text</td></tr><tr><td><code>awk</code></td><td>Process columns and fields</td></tr><tr><td><code>cut / sort / uniq / wc</code></td><td>Slice, order, dedupe, count</td></tr><tr><td><code>head / tail</code></td><td>Show top / bottom; tail -f follows</td></tr><tr><td><code>find</code></td><td>Locate files by criteria</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Putting the Filters Together</h3><p>The toolkit's value shows when you chain it. To find the top ten IPs in a web log you might run <code>awk '{print $1}' access.log | sort | uniq -c | sort -rn | head</code>: awk pulls the first field, the first sort groups identical lines so <code>uniq -c</code> can count them, and the second numeric reverse sort surfaces the busiest clients. Patterns are written as regular expressions, and the difference between basic and extended regex catches people out: <code>grep -E</code> (or <code>egrep</code>) enables <code>+</code>, <code>?</code>, and <code>|</code> without backslashes, while plain <code>grep</code> requires escaping them. Anchors <code>^</code> and <code>$</code> match start and end of line, and <code>grep -v</code> inverts the match to show non-matching lines -- invaluable for filtering noise out of logs.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Task</th><th>One-liner</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Count matching lines</td><td><code>grep -c error log</code></td></tr><tr><td>Print field 7 of a CSV</td><td><code>awk -F, '{print $7}' data.csv</code></td></tr><tr><td>Replace in place</td><td><code>sed -i 's/foo/bar/g' file</code></td></tr><tr><td>Sort numerically, descending</td><td><code>sort -rn</code></td></tr><tr><td>Files modified in last day</td><td><code>find . -mtime -1</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Text Editors</h3><p>Two editors matter. <span class='keyterm'>vi/vim</span> is universally present; it is modal, with a normal mode for navigation and an insert mode entered by <code>i</code>, returning with <code>Esc</code>, and saving and quitting with <code>:wq</code>. <span class='keyterm'>nano</span> is simpler and shows its shortcuts on screen (<code>Ctrl+O</code> to save, <code>Ctrl+X</code> to exit), making it friendlier for quick edits. Knowing the bare minimum of vi is non-negotiable because it is the one editor guaranteed to exist on a stripped-down server or in a rescue shell, where nano may not be installed.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Know that <code>2&gt;&amp;1</code> redirects stderr to the current stdout target, and order matters: <code>command &gt; file 2&gt;&amp;1</code> sends both to the file, but <code>command 2&gt;&amp;1 &gt; file</code> does not, because stderr is duplicated to the terminal before stdout is redirected.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"Backup, Restore, Archiving, and Compression", body:"<p>Protecting data is a core responsibility. Linux distinguishes <span class='keyterm'>archiving</span> (bundling many files into one) from <span class='keyterm'>compression</span> (shrinking data), and provides tools that do one or both, plus synchronization and block-level copying for full backups.</p><h3>tar: The Archiver</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>tar</span> (tape archive) bundles files and directories into a single <code>.tar</code> archive and is the workhorse of Linux backups. The three core operations are create (<code>c</code>), extract (<code>x</code>), and list (<code>t</code>), nearly always combined with <code>f</code> for the file name and often <code>v</code> for verbose. Add a compression flag to compress in one step: <code>z</code> for gzip, <code>j</code> for bzip2, <code>J</code> for xz. So <code>tar czf backup.tar.gz /etc</code> creates a gzip-compressed archive of <code>/etc</code>, and <code>tar xzf backup.tar.gz</code> extracts it.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>tar czf a.tgz dir/</code></td><td>Create gzip-compressed archive</td></tr><tr><td><code>tar xzf a.tgz</code></td><td>Extract a gzip archive</td></tr><tr><td><code>tar tf a.tar</code></td><td>List contents without extracting</td></tr><tr><td><code>tar cjf a.tbz dir/</code></td><td>Create bzip2-compressed archive</td></tr><tr><td><code>tar cJf a.txz dir/</code></td><td>Create xz-compressed archive</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Compression Tools and cpio</h3><p>Standalone compressors operate on single files: <span class='keyterm'>gzip</span> is fast and ubiquitous, <span class='keyterm'>bzip2</span> compresses tighter but slower, and <span class='keyterm'>xz</span> gives the best ratio at the highest CPU cost. View a compressed text file without unpacking using <code>zcat</code> (or <code>zless</code>). The <span class='keyterm'>cpio</span> tool is an older archiver still used by the initramfs and by RPM internally. The trade-off is consistent: the tighter the ratio, the more CPU and wall-clock time the compression takes, which matters when archiving terabytes nightly.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>tar flag</th><th>Ratio</th><th>Speed</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>gzip (.gz)</td><td><code>z</code></td><td>Good</td><td>Fast</td></tr><tr><td>bzip2 (.bz2)</td><td><code>j</code></td><td>Better</td><td>Slower</td></tr><tr><td>xz (.xz)</td><td><code>J</code></td><td>Best</td><td>Slowest</td></tr><tr><td>zstd (.zst)</td><td><code>--zstd</code></td><td>Good</td><td>Very fast</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>dd, ddrescue, and rsync</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>dd</span> copies data block by block and can clone an entire disk: <code>dd if=/dev/sda of=/dev/sdb bs=4M status=progress</code>. Because a wrong <code>of=</code> destroys data, dd has earned the nickname disk destroyer -- check arguments twice. <span class='keyterm'>ddrescue</span> is the right tool for failing disks because it retries and skips bad sectors to recover as much as possible. <span class='keyterm'>rsync</span> efficiently synchronizes directories, transferring only changed data: <code>rsync -av /src/ /dst/</code> preserves permissions and timestamps with archive mode, <code>--delete</code> removes destination files no longer in the source, and <code>rsync -avz -e ssh /src/ user@host:/dst/</code> mirrors over an encrypted SSH connection. A subtle but critical detail is the trailing slash on the source: <code>rsync -a /src/ /dst/</code> copies the contents of <code>src</code> into <code>dst</code>, while <code>rsync -a /src /dst/</code> copies the directory itself, creating <code>/dst/src</code>. Add <code>-n</code> (dry run) to preview exactly what would change before committing, and <code>--progress</code> to watch large transfers.</p><h3>Backup Types</h3><p>Three strategies trade backup speed against restore speed. A <span class='keyterm'>full backup</span> copies everything every time -- simplest to restore, slowest to run. An <span class='keyterm'>incremental backup</span> copies only what changed since the last backup of any kind -- fast and small, but restore requires the full plus every increment in order. A <span class='keyterm'>differential backup</span> copies everything changed since the last full backup -- larger than incrementals but restores from just the full plus one differential. The practical rule of thumb the exam rewards: incrementals minimize backup time and storage but maximize restore complexity, while differentials sit in the middle, and a full does the opposite of an incremental. A mature strategy combines them -- a weekly full plus nightly incrementals -- and is paired with the <span class='keyterm'>3-2-1 rule</span>: keep three copies of data, on two different media, with one copy off-site, so that a single fire, theft, or ransomware event cannot destroy every copy at once. Always test restores periodically, because a backup that has never been restored is only a hope, not a guarantee, and verify archives with <code>tar tf</code> or a checksum so silent corruption is caught before you need the data.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Backs up</th><th>Restore needs</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Full</td><td>Everything, every run</td><td>The full only</td></tr><tr><td>Incremental</td><td>Changes since last backup</td><td>Full + all increments</td></tr><tr><td>Differential</td><td>Changes since last full</td><td>Full + last differential</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>You need nightly off-site backups that finish quickly and minimize bandwidth. Use <code>rsync -avz --delete</code> over SSH to mirror only changed blocks to the remote host, and schedule a weekly full <code>tar</code> archive for point-in-time recovery. This pairs fast daily syncs with restorable snapshots, and pushing the weekly archive to a second medium and an off-site location satisfies the 3-2-1 rule.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[1].push(
  {heading:"Virtualization on Linux: KVM, QEMU, and Disk Images", body:"<p>Virtualization lets one physical host run many isolated guest operating systems. Linux is itself one of the most capable virtualization platforms, and the exam expects you to know the components, the disk image formats, and the network modes.</p><h3>Type 1 versus Type 2 Hypervisors</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>hypervisor</span> is the layer that creates and runs virtual machines. A <span class='keyterm'>Type 1 (bare-metal)</span> hypervisor runs directly on hardware with no host OS beneath it -- examples include VMware ESXi and the Linux-based approach where KVM turns the kernel into a hypervisor. A <span class='keyterm'>Type 2 (hosted)</span> hypervisor runs as an application on top of a normal OS, like VirtualBox or VMware Workstation; it is more convenient but adds overhead.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Type 1 (bare-metal)</th><th>Type 2 (hosted)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Runs on</td><td>Hardware directly</td><td>A host operating system</td></tr><tr><td>Performance</td><td>Higher</td><td>Lower (extra layer)</td></tr><tr><td>Examples</td><td>KVM, ESXi, Hyper-V</td><td>VirtualBox, VMware Workstation</td></tr><tr><td>Typical use</td><td>Servers, data centers</td><td>Desktops, labs, testing</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>KVM, QEMU, and libvirt</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>KVM</span> (Kernel-based Virtual Machine) is a kernel module that uses CPU virtualization extensions (Intel VT-x or AMD-V) to run guests at near-native speed. KVM provides the CPU and memory virtualization, while <span class='keyterm'>QEMU</span> emulates the rest of the virtual hardware (disks, network, display); the two together form a complete VM. Managing them by hand is tedious, so <span class='keyterm'>libvirt</span> provides a stable management API, the <code>virsh</code> command-line tool, and the <code>virt-manager</code> GUI. Typical commands are <code>virsh list --all</code>, <code>virsh start web01</code>, and <code>virsh shutdown web01</code>. Guest definitions are stored as XML under <code>/etc/libvirt/qemu/</code>, edited safely with <code>virsh edit web01</code>. A prerequisite that trips people up is hardware virtualization: if <code>grep -E 'vmx|svm' /proc/cpuinfo</code> returns nothing, the CPU extensions are disabled in firmware and KVM will fall back to slow pure emulation.</p><table><thead><tr><th>virsh command</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>virsh list --all</code></td><td>Show all defined guests and state</td></tr><tr><td><code>virsh start / shutdown &lt;vm&gt;</code></td><td>Power a guest on / gracefully off</td></tr><tr><td><code>virsh destroy &lt;vm&gt;</code></td><td>Force-stop (pull the plug)</td></tr><tr><td><code>virsh autostart &lt;vm&gt;</code></td><td>Start the guest at host boot</td></tr><tr><td><code>virsh edit &lt;vm&gt;</code></td><td>Edit the guest's XML definition</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>VirtIO and Disk Image Formats</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>VirtIO</span> drivers are paravirtualized devices: instead of emulating real hardware, the guest uses lightweight virtual devices that know they are virtualized, giving much faster disk and network performance. Guests store their disks as image files. The <span class='keyterm'>raw</span> format is a flat byte-for-byte image -- fast and simple but consuming full size up front. The <span class='keyterm'>qcow2</span> (QEMU Copy-On-Write 2) format is thin-provisioned, growing as data is written, and supports internal snapshots and compression. Convert between formats with <code>qemu-img convert -O qcow2 disk.raw disk.qcow2</code>, and inspect with <code>qemu-img info disk.qcow2</code>; create a fresh thin image with <code>qemu-img create -f qcow2 disk.qcow2 40G</code>, which reserves almost no space until the guest writes. Cloud images ship as qcow2 and are customized at first boot by <span class='keyterm'>cloud-init</span>, which reads user data to set the hostname, inject SSH keys, and run provisioning scripts -- the mechanism behind nearly every cloud instance and a frequent exam topic. To prepare a generic template you run <code>virt-sysprep</code> to strip host-specific identifiers such as SSH host keys and machine IDs before cloning, otherwise every clone would share an identity.</p><h3>Snapshots, Nesting, and Virtual Networks</h3><p>A VM <span class='keyterm'>snapshot</span> captures the guest's disk and optionally memory state so you can roll back after a risky change. <span class='keyterm'>Nested virtualization</span> runs a hypervisor inside a VM, useful for labs and cloud-based test environments, and requires the host to expose its virtualization extensions to the guest. Virtual networking offers several modes that the exam tests directly, and the choice determines whether a guest is reachable from the rest of the LAN or hidden behind the host.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Network type</th><th>Behavior</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>NAT</td><td>Guests share the host's IP; outbound only by default</td></tr><tr><td>Bridged</td><td>Guest gets an IP on the physical LAN, peer to the host</td></tr><tr><td>Host-only / isolated</td><td>Guests talk to host and each other, no external access</td></tr><tr><td>Routed</td><td>Guests on a separate subnet the host routes for</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>If a guest must appear as a normal machine on the physical network with its own LAN IP, choose <strong>bridged</strong> networking. If it only needs outbound internet and should stay hidden behind the host, <strong>NAT</strong> is correct. And prefer <code>qcow2</code> over <code>raw</code> when you need snapshots and thin provisioning.</div>"}
);
